{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_23","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' references_cache/PMID_21102469.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nreference_id: PMID:21102469\ntitle: Prephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via arogenate.\nauthors:\n- Maeda H\n- Yoo H\n- Dudareva N\njournal: Nat Chem Biol\nyear: '2011'\ndoi: 10.1038/nchembio.485\nkeywords:\n- Carbon Cycle/physiology\n- Humans\n- Hydro-Lyases/metabolism\n- Phenylalanine/biosynthesis\n- Plant Proteins/biosynthesis\n- Plants/enzymology\n- Transaminases/metabolism\n- \"Tyrosine/analogs & derivatives, biosynthesis\"\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---\n\n# Prephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via arogenate.\n**Authors:** Maeda H, Yoo H, Dudareva N\n**Journal:** Nat Chem Biol (2011)\n**DOI:** [10.1038/nchembio.485](https://doi.org/10.1038/nchembio.485)\n\n## Content\n\n1. Nat Chem Biol. 2011 Jan;7(1):19-21. doi: 10.1038/nchembio.485. Epub 2010 Nov\n21.\n\nPrephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via \narogenate.\n\nMaeda H(1), Yoo H, Dudareva N.\n\nAuthor information:\n(1)Department of Horticulture and Landscape Architecture, Purdue University, \nWest Lafayette, Indiana, USA.\n\nThe aromatic amino acids L-phenylalanine and L-tyrosine and their plant-derived \nnatural products are essential in human and plant metabolism and physiology. \nHere we identified Petunia hybrida and Arabidopsis thaliana genes encoding \nprephenate aminotransferases (PPA-ATs), thus completing the identification of \nthe genes involved in phenylalanine and tyrosine biosyntheses. Biochemical and \ngenetic characterization of enzymes showed that PPA-AT directs carbon flux from \nprephenate toward arogenate, making the arogenate pathway predominant in plant \nphenylalanine biosynthesis.\n\nDOI: 10.1038/nchembio.485\nPMID: 21102469 [Indexed for MEDLINE]","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
